column11: During his campaign, President-elect Trump vowed to deport millions of unauthorized immigrants (USA Today, Donald J. Trump for President, Inc., Washington Post). U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) tracks removals for each fiscal year (U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement); in the 2016 fiscal year, they conducted 240,255 (ICE). The government's 2017 fiscal year runs from 1 October 2016 through 30 September 2017. The question will be suspended on 30 September 2017 and closed when ICE releases its data, typically in December. Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

“The U.S. is deporting people more slowly than during the Obama administration despite President Donald Trump’s vast immigration crackdown, according to new data from U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement. From Feb. 1 to June 30, ICE officials removed 84,473 people -- a rate of roughly 16,900 people per month. If deportations continue at the same clip until the fiscal year ends Sept. 30, federal immigration officials will have removed fewer people than they did during even the slowest years of Barack Obama’s presidency. In fiscal year 2016, ICE removed 240,255 people from the country, a rate of more than 20,000 people per month.” http://politi.co/2vifRRu

If current trends continue, removal rates are trending below 250K (https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2017/07/17/immigration-arrests-up-deportations-down-under-trump/484437001/#). Using the monthly averages in the article (22,705/mo for Oct-Dec and 16,895/mo for Feb-Jun), using the 22,705 number for Jan to fill the gap for a higher end result, and carrying forward the 16,895 number for the remainder of the FY (3 mos), the number shakes out to about 226K (22,705*4 mos plus 16,895*8 mos). It's possible for increases in the last few months, but as the article noted, EOIR case backlog is now above 600K. As I've mentioned in other posts (https://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/529938, https://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/495969, and https://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/494679), this backlog and the challenges of removing large numbers of immigrants makes it unlikely the administration will be able to remove an additional 25K over the next 3 months to get above 250K.

https://qz.com/976181/trump-has-decided-not-to-spend-on-the-one-thing-that-could-really-deter-illegal-immigration/ "Congress’s spending bill calls for 10 additional judges, but a look at the math suggests a lot more are needed. ... As of March, cases had been sitting there for an average of 669 days, up from 413 days a decade ago, according to Syracuse University’s Transactional Records Access Clearinghouse, or TRAC, which gathers such data. ... The EOIR budget seems similarly insufficient for the workload. There are roughly 570,000 cases pending in court, according to TRAC. EOIR currently has funding for 374 judges, though only 311 of those positions have been filled. Each judge can process about 750 cases a year. Even with the 10 additional judges under the spending bill—and assuming those and all the other vacant judgeships could be filled and trained up immediately, which they won’t be—it would still take nearly two years to get through the current backlog. By which time even more cases will be waiting."

This question hinges on how much the number of removals is really in Trump's control. On the one hand, border apprehensions for the last three years are down, and this is no doubt a key reason why removals are down, too. But another reasons might have to do with Obama's 2015 executive orders, which called for a focus on deporting convicted felons over non-criminals. Trump's reversal of these orders might contribute to higher deportation rates.

Looking at EOIR (immigration) court data (https://www.justice.gov/eoir/page/file/fysb16/download), it appears that proceedings for removal have a 70% chance of ending in the migrant being removed at the initial case, with 96K migrants being removed in 2016 during initial case proceedings. If the case is referred to subsequent proceedings, which happens about 10% of the time, the percentage of verdicts for removal drops to about 30%, with 4.4 migrants removed after subsequent proceedings.
